{"cursor":"30172","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematical logic, the 'Peano axioms', also known as the 'DedekindâPeano\naxioms' or the 'Peano postulates', are a set of axioms for the natural numbers\npresented by the 19th century Italian mathematician Giuseppe Peano. These axioms\nhave been used nearly unchanged in a number of metamathematical investigations,\nincluding research into fundamental questions of consistency and completeness of\nnumber theory.\n\nThe need for formalism in arithmetic was not well appreciated until the work of\nHermann Grassmann, who showed in the 1860s that many facts in arithmetic could\nbe derived from more basic facts about the successor operation and\ninduction. Grassmann 1861 In 1881, Charles Sanders Peirce provided an\naxiomatization of natural-number arithmetic. Peirce 1881; also see Shields\n1997 In 1888, Richard Dedekind proposed a collection of axioms about\nthe numbers, and in 1889 Peano published a more precisely formulated\nversion of them as a collection of axioms in his book, The principles of\narithmetic presented by a new method ().\n\nThe Peano axioms contain three types of statements. The first axiom asserts the\nexistence of at least one member of the set \"number\". The next four are general\nstatements about equality; in modern treatments these are often considered\naxioms of the \"underlying logic\". van Heijenoort 1967:94 The next\nthree axioms are first-order statements about natural numbers expressing the\nfundamental properties of the successor operation. The ninth, final axiom is a\nsecond order statement of the principle of mathematical induction over the\nnatural numbers. A weaker first-order system called 'Peano arithmetic' is\nobtained by explicitly adding the addition and multiplication operation symbols\nand replacing the second-order induction axiom with a first-order axiom schema.\n","linknr":395,"url":"Peano_Arithmetic","recorded":1362374580,"links":32,"instances":["algebra","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","mathematical_logic","mathematics","mathematical_logic","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["1889 introductions","Mathematical axioms","Formal theories of arithmetic","Logic in computer science","Mathematical logic"],"headings":["The axioms","Arithmetic","Models","Consistency","See also","Footnotes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/5/b/e5b2e1e7459ccc17ef8193b7bd6f7aea.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/5/d/95dd1dc28b7774e45c5be05328e4612c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/9/0/7904c158853cd6592c9c9ca6a81b87c4.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/5/b/e5b1729460efb19cb2147ff65bede448.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/c/3/9c3ba4c2bb2f25702bc6685df3812917.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/f/e/3fe55c2696c63f12734e3b265c48b73a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/6/f/66f4b7daa7583d220f93487fec84d542.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/0/8/b08332264b4c93f6866822c77a715712.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/4/b/b4b4902d8e12ad2b147f1e2aca17edfc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/5/9/259f01699160cb0c941d36272b442997.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/a/e/2aec93babf8fa5b7014c795b3c78a660.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/9/6/7966d4efd165ae0c6103ccd41d921d11.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/0/b/10b9fdacffcecc3574e9306610427486.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/6/d/96d9477aaa5a701de346295953884ff2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/5/c/75cb9f811d92fc0603f5077c53a6e136.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/5/8/8588238b0f2759516cc4f6b6cefe311b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/9/a/89ad9a225e31c3711e63b56c2fb42601.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/6/d/96d9477aaa5a701de346295953884ff2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/0/e/c0e7cf86a0da0501c6cc09ba356d77c5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/5/8/8588238b0f2759516cc4f6b6cefe311b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/7/3/473ae336994a9066480c735b576cab44.png","//upload.